{
  "id": "019d33db-5684-7441-aeab-9d6f18fc1bed",
  "content": "# 5-Persona Review: Multi-Spoke Design (2026-03-28)\n\n## Verdicts: 4x \"With fixes\", 1x \"No\" (Security)\n\n## 8 Critical Issues\n- HubContext panics on unmapped paths\n- No duplicate spoke name guard\n- OAuth token expiry in long-running spokes\n- No rollback on partial creation failure\n- HubContext fails outside containers\n- Non-deterministic Docker network selection\n- MCP endpoint on 0.0.0.0 with NO authentication (Security blocker)\n- No failure UX for headless spoke operations\n\n## 13 Important Issues\nGITHUB_TOKEN validation, resource limits, agent identity spoofing, supply chain (npm @latest), token scope, test plan, startup error reporting, clone depth, usage agreement, branch naming, hub restart resilience, disk exhaustion, spoke permissions\n\n## Key Security Findings\nMCP endpoint has zero auth. Any container on Docker network can write/delete knowledge, change config, run GC. Must add bearer token auth before deployment. Agent identity is self-declared env var with no server-side verification.\n\n## Consensus: Architecture is sound, hardening needed before production.\n\nDoc: docs/decisions/2026-03-28-spoke-design-review-summary.md",
  "source_version": "mcp",
